<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-259-212  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 259 212.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  May 8 1989 v23 n19 p91(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The difference between conservation and cutoff. (includes relatedarticle on advice from three companies that have automated)(Restructuring: Data Center Automation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Stevens, Larry.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Data center managers are interested in the concept of totalautomation, but so far are only selectively automating theiroperations.andP;  'Lights-out,' or unattended operations, would cutcosts considerably, but would also entail massive layoffs andmajor corporate restructurings.andP;  Companies that have implementedsome level of automation have usually focused on tape libraries,console systems and job scheduling systems.andP;  Of 350 companiessurveyed, 20 percent are planning automation, 60 percent hadimplemented automation for message suppression only, and 20percent are working toward full automation.andP;  In the opinion ofsome managers, the goal of completely unattended operations ismisleading.andP;  They believe that the human element cannot beentirely removed from every aspect of data center operations.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Information CentersOperations ManagersAutomationTechnology-Induced Unemployment.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographgraph.andO;Caption:   What the big boys use. (graph)Stages of automation. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>